[('Kermes (insect)', 'Kermes is a genus of scale insects in the order Hemiptera. They feed on the sap of evergreen oaks; the females produce a red dye, also called kermes, that is the source of natural crimson. The word kermes is derived from Persian or Turkish qirmiz or kirmizi (قرمز), crimson (both the colour and the dyestuff).There are some 20 species, including:\n\nKermes bacciformis Leonardi, 1908\nKermes corticalis (Nassonov, 1908)\nKermes echinatus (Balachowsky, 1953)\nKermes gibbosus Signoret, 1875\nKermes ilicis (Linnaeus, 1758)\nKermes roboris (Fourcroy, 1785)\nKermes vermilio Planchon, 1864', ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/67/Ceroplastes_ceriferus_from_CSIRO.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9b/Kermes_echinatus_Balachowsky_mature_reproductive_females_-_ZooKeys-246-011-g002.jpeg']), ('Kermes vermilio', 'Kermes vermilio is one of the species of Kermes used to make the crimson dye also called kermes.', ['https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/67/Ceroplastes_ceriferus_from_CSIRO.jpg', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/74/Red_Pencil_Icon.png', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/9/99/Question_book-new.svg'])]